  "prompt": "Why do Indians follow rules when they are in a foreign country but fail to do so in their own country?",
  "response": "This is a complex social and psychological issue that can be attributed to several factors:\n\n1. Strict enforcement of laws\n- Foreign countries have stricter law enforcement\n- Consequences for breaking rules are more severe and consistently applied\n- Higher probability of facing legal or professional repercussions\n\n2. Cultural conditioning\n- Respect for host country's systems\n- Desire to maintain a positive image as immigrants\n- Fear of deportation or visa complications\n\n3. Systemic differences in India\n- Weak law enforcement\n- Complex bureaucratic processes\n- Corruption and inconsistent rule implementation\n- Social acceptance of rule-bending\n\n4. Psychological factors\n- Lack of collective civic sense\n- Individual convenience prioritized over societal rules\n- Limited sense of personal responsibility\n\n5. Infrastructure challenges\n- Inadequate infrastructure can make rule-following difficult\n- Overcrowding and resource constraints\n\n6. Social conditioning\n- Historical tolerance for flexible interpretation of rules\n- Jugaad (innovative problem-solving) culture\n\nThese factors contribute to different behavioral patterns, but it's important to note that this doesn't apply to all Indians, and many citizens are actively working to improve civic behavior and rule adherence.\n\nEach individual's attitude towards rules varies, and generalizations should be avoided.",
